    "summary": "The Edicts of Ashoka (264–232 BC) are a series of proclamations inscribed on rocks, cave walls, and polished sandstone pillars across the [[event:74|Maurya Empire (India)]] by Emperor [[event:1098|Ashoka the Great]], representing the first substantial epigraphic tradition in South Asia and one of antiquity's most remarkable collections of royal proclamations. Written in Prakrit (and in some western areas in Greek and Aramaic), they constitute the primary historical sources for Ashoka's reign and Buddhist expansion.\n\nThe edicts cover a wide range of subjects: the [[event:1099|Kalinga War]]'s aftermath and Ashoka's remorse; policies of religious tolerance commanding respect for all sects; animal welfare measures including reductions in meat eating and hunting at court; medical facilities for humans and animals; welfare infrastructure (wells, rest houses, trees planted along roads); humane treatment of prisoners including the right to request pardon; and guidelines for officials on governing by dharma (moral law).\n\nThe texts are self-consciously addressed to Ashoka's subjects and to posterity — he repeatedly expresses hope that his policies will endure and that future generations will learn from them. This unusual directness makes the edicts a remarkable psychological document as well as a historical source. The Ashoka pillars, with their polished surfaces and elaborate capital sculptures — most famously the Lion Capital now India's national symbol — were engineering feats as well as vehicles for Ashoka's message. The script used in most edicts (Brahmi) is the ancestor of virtually all modern South and Southeast Asian writing systems.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edicts_of_Ashoka",
